Good validation query

Run this to compare PCP_IND against specialty description:

SELECT
    p.PCP_IND,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE,
    COUNT(*) AS CNT
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON p.PROVIDER_ID = s.PROVIDER_ID
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE p.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
GROUP BY
    p.PCP_IND,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
ORDER BY CNT DESC;

This will tell you whether:

Y / 1 lines up with PCP specialties
N / 0 lines up with specialist specialties
Practical way to define specialist for now

A good first-pass filter is:

WHERE COALESCE(TRIM(PCP_IND), '') IN ('0', 'N')

But because blanks are huge, better is:

WHERE COALESCE(TRIM(PCP_IND), '') NOT IN ('1', 'Y')

That means:

exclude known PCPs
keep non-PCP and blank values

But this can include unknowns, so it is broader.

Safer version

If you want only strong specialist candidates:

WHERE COALESCE(TRIM(PCP_IND), '') IN ('0', 'N')

If you want broader specialist candidate capture:

WHERE COALESCE(TRIM(PCP_IND), '') NOT IN ('1', 'Y')
My recommendation

For your research spike, use this approach:

Known PCP
COALESCE(TRIM(p.PCP_IND), '') IN ('1', 'Y')
Known non-PCP
COALESCE(TRIM(p.PCP_IND), '') IN ('0', 'N')
Unknown
COALESCE(TRIM(p.PCP_IND), '') = ''

