Better summary logic

For your final specialist visit logic, I would use:

CASE
    WHEN COALESCE(TRIM(p.PCP_IND), '') IN ('1', 'Y') THEN 'PCP'
    WHEN COALESCE(TRIM(p.PCP_IND), '') IN ('0', 'N') THEN 'NON_PCP'
    ELSE 'UNKNOWN'
END

That gives you a cleaner classification.

Example:

SELECT
    p.PROVIDER_ID,
    p.PROVIDER_FULL_NAME,
    p.NPI_ID,
    p.PCP_IND,
    CASE
        WHEN COALESCE(TRIM(p.PCP_IND), '') IN ('1', 'Y') THEN 'PCP'
        WHEN COALESCE(TRIM(p.PCP_IND), '') IN ('0', 'N') THEN 'NON_PCP'
        ELSE 'UNKNOWN'
    END AS PCP_CLASS,
    s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON p.PROVIDER_ID = s.PROVIDER_ID
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE p.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1;
Plain-English takeaway

Yes — your results suggest:

1 and Y probably mean PCP
0 and N probably mean non-PCP
blank means unknown/not populated

Because blank is huge, you should not use PCP_IND alone to define specialist visits. Use it together with specialty code/description.

